   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Using Spatial Joins"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import transportation_tutorials as tt\n",
    "import geopandas as gpd\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "from shapely.geometry import Point"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Questions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "1. Within the SERPM 7 region, what TAZ has the largest number of MAZs within its \n",
    "   boundary?  How many does it have?\n",
    "2. Generate a map of the MAZ boundaries within this TAZ, including context as necessary \n",
    "   from OpenStreetMaps.  What features of this TAZ helped lead to the large number of \n",
    "   MAZ's?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To answer the questions, use the following files:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "maz = gpd.read_file(tt.data('SERPM8-MAZSHAPE'))\n",
    "taz = gpd.read_file(tt.data('SERPM8-TAZSHAPE'))"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Solution"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We use `.sjoin()` method in `geopandas` to perform spatial join between two different spatial resolutions. For this exercise, we need to join MAZs with TAZs and we do that based on TAZ polygons and MAZ centroids. For this purpose, we will create a new geo-dataframe for MAZs with centroids in the `geometry` column. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "maz_centroids = maz.copy()\n",
    "maz_centroids.geometry = maz_centroids.apply(lambda x: Point(x.POINT_X, x.POINT_Y), axis = 1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we use `.sjoin()` method with `op = 'within'` to indicate that MAZ centroids must be located within TAZ polygons. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "taz_maz = gpd.sjoin(maz_centroids, taz, how = 'left', op = 'within')"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then, we simply use `.groupby()` method to prepare our answer. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "taz_maz_counts = taz_maz.groupby(['TAZ_REG'])['MAZ'].count()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can find the maximum number of MAZ's within a TAZ by taking the\n",
    "`max` of this grouping result."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "16"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "taz_maz_counts.max()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `idxmax` will give us the index value (i.e., the TAZ id) of the TAZ with the largest\n",
    "number of MAZ's."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
